@Rover [τ, τ] I can answer this, a bit of a history lesson. The Kusanagi chain was attacked by one of the core developer/founders of this project in around March 2021. We decided to hard fork the network to Nakamoto without those funds. Technically that chain is still running and you can access it through the previous entrypoints.
woah. I want to hear this story

Kusanagi was intended to the main network but we decided it was unstable to have such a large number of funds, "rouge" early on in a network where stake plays an large roll in the incentive mechanism.
The difference in that chart is the difference between what was and was not copied directly across to the nakamoto chain.
But you had a developer attack the network? what happened to them?
They left the project, there are no hard feelings, they did the right thing.
Wow thanks @consτ [τ, τ]  - I think I'm getting to know some interesting things!
Speaking of attacks - what are the various attack vectors / risks you foresee? What is your view on "pools" - pros/cons?

Another Q: I know this question may seem silly but what would be advantages/efficiencies of Bittensor vs the centralized AI giants? When one would want to choose between the two?  Would the centralized AI giants be incentivized to join something like Bittensor and contribute to the market place/AI research?

I would say the "biggest cabal" attack, where they create a hard fork and have the ability to control who gets what. Usually the biggest cabal survives because they ping each other. Another problem (that I see mostly) is singeling out: if you have an sub-optimal system, and they cannot ping you often enough, you might get dumped off the network despite being trustworthy and having something unique to share.
That is why I like "pools". They have the power to form single-entity cabals, especially when you have to do PoW to get on the network, a pool helps with that.

@Rover [τ, τ] good Qs. Re attack vector:s the biggest attack vector is the one defined in the paper where a large portion of the stake splits the consensus and takes over the network emission. Unlike say POW where an attacker needs to maintain the work to hold the position, in a POS system like ours this is a devastating event -- hence our choice of fair launch which was both the most ethical one and practical one given the need for token decentralization. Other known attacks are things like DDOS which could throw the system off until the miners built defenses. Clogging the registration system is also possible, e.g. registering for no reason but to fill the slots, this would be like filling the Bitcoin blockchain with empty transactions. Finally, security wise we are open to issues while the system remains centralized around the ability for the developers to perform hard forks with the sudo keys, this will change after we get a parachain slot and introduce democracy. 

Re: value prop: In short, incentivized infrastructure scales us to Bitcoin size and allows us to surpass Google, OpenAI in compute.  Why? because we are using digital trust to revolutionize the way we create and measure machine intelligence, moving away from a slow moving, low resolution, biased, academic, human mediated mechanism towards one which is, well, the opposite of those things. Firms want in, cause they want to connect their machine learning systems into the best source of machine knowledge.
Thanks for your response!
Appreciate your response!  I hope Bittensor becomes the "Trustless Machine Intelligence" 😇
